==English==
===Etymology (1)===
[[inter-]] + [[-nym]].  The word was apparently invented by Madeleine Page in the Internet newsgroup <tt>alt.folklore.urban</tt>.

====Noun====
{{en-noun-reg}}
# ''(Internet)'' A phrase or [[epithet]], particularly one intended to be [[witty]], inserted in quotation marks between one's first and last names—or elsewhere by or in one's name, if this is not possible—at the end of a [[post]].

====Quotations====
* '''1997,''' Madeleine Page in <tt>alt.folklore.urban</tt> [http://groups.google.com/group/alt.folklore.urban/msg/9c095dc5d92686ff?dmode=source&hl=en]
*: Madeleine "'''internym''' goes here" Page
* '''1998,''' Rick Denney, in <tt>rec.sport.triathlon</tt> [http://groups.google.com/group/rec.sport.triathlon/msg/21799ee04a8dee81?dmode=source&hl=en]
*: I'm experimenting with the '''internym''' after seeing it so artfully used by others on other newsgroups.
* '''2005,''' Michael Kuettner in <tt>alt.folklore.urban</tt> [http://groups.google.com/group/alt.folklore.urban/msg/f147df0122ec740c?dmode=source]
*: Michael "please destroy that message after reading[5]" Kuettner[6]
*: [...]
*: [5] This '''internym''' was inserted by the NSA to discredit [1]


===Etymology (2)===
Apparently a blend of [[Internet]] and [[acronym]].

====Noun====
# {{rfv-sense}} An acronym commonly in use on the Internet, such as "lol" for "laughing out loud" or "fwiw" for "for what it's worth".  Internyms are used to make certain common phrases more compact.

